Reference for the `sbc_germany` benchmark — Synthetic Business Cycle (SBC),
Shi, Xi & Xie (2025), "A Synthetic Business Cycle Approach to Counterfactual
Analysis with Nonstationary Macroeconomic Data," arXiv:2505.22388.
Authors' code: github.com/jinxi-atlas/Synthetic-business-cycle-code (no licence).

Files
- reference.R       mlsynth's runner: the authors' SBC method (lsq Hamilton
                    detrending + trend_predict forecast + Synth::synth on the
                    cyclical / level components), reproduced from Germany.R with
                    the plotting removed, run on the authoritative
                    basedata/german_reunification.csv.
- golden_steps.R    Emits per-step golden values (treated/donor cycles, trend
                    coefficients, trend forecast, and the authors' Synth weights
                    + cyclical SSE) on basedata/repgermany.dta, for the unit
                    tests in mlsynth/tests/test_sbc_reference.py.
- golden_steps.txt  Captured output of golden_steps.R (committed so the tests
                    need no R toolchain).
- reference.json / reference.out / provenance.json
                    Captured run of reference.R (the authors' Synth::synth
                    output, version-pinned).

What the cross-validation found
- mlsynth's Hamilton detrending and trend forecast reproduce the authors' lsq /
  trend_predict to ~1e-8.
- The synthetic-control step is the one divergence, and mlsynth is the more
  accurate implementation: the authors' Synth::synth (slack ipop tolerances)
  under-converges to a cyclical SSE ~2.6% above the optimum; mlsynth's simplex
  solver attains the verified global optimum (cvxpy agrees to machine
  precision). So the case pins mlsynth's optimum, NOT the authors' Synth output.
- The upstream repo's shipped wide Germany.csv permutes its donor column labels
  (its "Japan"/"Portugal" hold the Netherlands'/Greece's series, per the
  canonical repgermany.dta), so the paper's printed donor names ("Italy, Japan,
  Portugal") are mislabelled; the correctly-labelled optimum is Greece /
  Netherlands / Italy.

The authors' code/data are reproduced here for offline replication of this
benchmark only; all credit to the authors.
